a Binary encoding: 1 = Yes/Present/Hybrid/Transplanted, 0 = No/Absent/Inbred/Direct seeded.
The feature set encompassed eight pre-planting variables (X_1-X_8) related to land preparation, establishment decisions, and irrigation access; nine nutrient management variables (X_9-X_17) capturing fertilization practices; nine pest and disease variables (X_18-X_26) documenting challenges and management responses; and one environmental variable (X_27) accounting for weather-related challenges during the season.
This format directly reflected the activity-based categorization framework documented in the qualitative and quantitative findings. Pre-planting features (X_1-X_8) operationalized the universal transplanting practice (100% of farmers, Table 6, Theme I1), variety preferences (83% hybrid, Table 9), seed rate variation (median 18 kg, IQR 15-30 kg, Table 9), land preparation methods (98% tractor use, 65% rotavator, Table 9), and irrigation availability (100% NIA access, Table 9) identified during Phase 1 investigations.
Nutrient management features (X_9-X_17) operationalized the multi-stage fertilization patterns documented in 100% farmer interviews (Table 6, Theme I9) and quantitative surveys (Table 7, Table 9). Rather than recording raw fertilizer product quantities (which varied across five common formulations: Urea 46-0-0, Ammonium Sulfate 21-0-0, Ammonium Phosphate 16-20-0, Complete 14-14-14, Potash 0-0-60 documented in Table 7), features X_9-X_17 represent standardized NPK nutrient content computed as detailed in Equations [7]-[9]. This standardization addressed the wide variation in fertilizer products and timing documented in Table 9 while enabling model training on nutrient-equivalent units aligned with agronomic principles (DA-ATI CAR, 2022).
Pest and disease features (X_18-X_22) captured the five key challenges identified through thematic analysis: stem borer (89% prevalence, Table 9), golden apple snail/kuhol (63%), rats (13%), cutworms (6%), and rice blast (19%). These binary presence indicators reflected the preventive IPM orientation documented in qualitative findings (Table 6, Theme I4: 10/11 reported limited routine insecticide use) rather than severity gradations, as farmers consistently described pest management in present/absent rather than quantitative severity terms. 
Pest management input features (X_23-X_26) quantified protection product usage: insecticide (median 0 L), herbicide (median 0.5 L), rat poison (median 0 g), and molluscicide (median 0 sachets), aligning with the concentrated application windows around establishment documented in both qualitative interviews and quantitative patterns (Table 9).
The environmental challenge variable (X_27) operationalized the weather-related constraints reported by 80% of farmers (Table 9), including flooding near transplanting and dry-season water stress documented in qualitative accounts (Table 6, Themes I7-I8). While detailed meteorological covariates (rainfall amount, temperature, wind speed) were excluded due to data availability constraints identified in the constraint analysis discussed in the previous section, the binary weather challenge indicator captured farmer-perceived weather impacts on the growing season.
The complete 27-feature specification established the input variable framework for subsequent model development, with each feature directly traceable to empirical observations from farmer interviews and surveys. This traceability ensured that the predictive model would accept inputs aligned with actual farming practices and decision-making contexts documented during requirements planning, supporting the development of a decision-support tool grounded in local agricultural realities rather than theoretical or externally-imposed variable selections.
Model Development and Hyperparameter Optimization
Following the feature set specification derived from Phase 1, the model development phase focused on training, optimizing, and validating a Random Forest Regressor for palay yield prediction using the 27 input features (X_1-X_27) and the target variable Y (palay yield in kilograms). This section presents the hyperparameter search process, the optimal model configuration, and performance evaluation on the held-out test set.
Hyperparameter search and optimal configuration
The hyperparameter optimization process evaluated 216 Random Forest configurations through 3-fold cross-validation on the training set (presented in Table 5). A total of 54 farms were included in the analysis, yielding 37 training samples (70%) and 17 test samples (30%) following the 70-30 split procedure detailed in the methodology. Table 13 presents the optimal hyperparameter configuration that achieved the highest cross-validation performance among all evaluated combinations. 
The optimal configuration balanced model complexity (200 trees with maximum depth 10) against overfitting risk (controlled through max_depth constraint and feature subsampling via max_features=‘sqrt’). The max_depth=10 constraint prevented individual trees from growing excessively deep and memorizing training data, while the ‘sqrt’ feature selection ensured each split considered approximately 5 randomly selected features from the full set of 27, promoting diversity among the 200 trees in the ensemble (James et al., 2023b). The grid search identified this configuration as achieving the highest mean cross-validation R^2 of 0.6040 ± 0.1043 across the three folds, indicating consistent performance across different training/validation splits within the 70% training set. Complete evaluation results for all hyperparameter combinations are provided in Appendix Table 6 for transparency and reproducibility.
Table 13. Optimal Random Forest hyperparameters identified through grid search.
Hyperparameter	Selected Value	Interpretation
n_estimators	200	200 decision trees in the ensemble
max_depth	10	Maximum tree depth of 10 levels
min_samples_split	2	Minimum 2 samples required to split a node
min_samples_leaf	1	Minimum 1 sample required at a leaf node 
max_features	'sqrt'	√27  ≈ 5 features considered at each split 
Test set performance
The optimized Random Forest model, trained on 37 farms, was evaluated on a held-out test set of 17 farms (30% of the dataset) that were not used during training or hyperparameter optimization. Table 14 presents the performance metrics on this independent test set.
The test set R^2 of 0.765 indicates that the model explains approximately 76.5% of yield variance in previously unseen farms. The unexplained 23.5% likely reflects unmeasured variables excluded during Phase 1 due to data availability constraints, including quantitative weather data (rainfall amounts, temperature extremes), soil quality differences, and management execution quality. This performance aligns with related agricultural studies using ensemble methods on small datasets (David, 2023: R^2=0.78; Jiya et al., 2023: R^2=0.72).
The RMSE of 2,286 kg corresponds to approximately 36% of the median yield (6,287 kg, Table 9), reflecting the substantial variability documented in Phase 1 (yield range 1,220-20,790 kg driven by farm size heterogeneity, seed quality variation, fertilizer rate differences, and weather challenges affecting 80% of farmers). The MAE of 1,731 kg, being lower than RMSE, indicates that while typical errors are moderate, occasional larger errors occur at the distribution's extremes. 
Table 14. Performance metrics of the optimized Random Forest model on the hold-out test set (n=17 farms).
Metric	Value
R^2 (coefficient of determination)	0.765
RMSE (root mean squared error)	2,286 kg
MAE (mean absolute error)	1,731 kg
MSE (mean squared error)	5,225,856 kg²

 
Fig. 20. Predicted versus actual yield for training (blue) and test (orange) sets. The dashed line represents perfect 1:1 agreement. Test samples maintain reasonable alignment despite not being used during training, demonstrating generalization.
To visualize the model's prediction behavior across the full yield range, Fig. 20 presents the relationship between predicted and actual yields for both training and test sets.
Points cluster more tightly in the mid-yield range (5,000-13,000 kg) where Phase 1 observations concentrated (median 6,287 kg, IQR 4,410-10,434 kg), with greater dispersion at extremes reflecting sparse training data (<4,000 kg and >15,000 kg). Test samples distribute along the diagonal similarly to training samples, confirming generalization rather than memorization. While Fig. 20 shows overall prediction alignment with actual yields, residual analysis provides deeper insight into error patterns and potential systematic bias. Fig. 21 presents residuals (actual minus predicted yield) for both datasets.
Residuals scatter randomly around zero without systematic patterns (funnel shapes, curves), with most within ±3,000 kg. This validates suggesting that the 27 features derived from Phase 1 explorations (activity-based organization: pre-planting, nutrient management, pest management, environmental challenges) captured many of the key yield drivers. The balanced distribution above and below zero confirms absence of systematic over- or under-prediction.
Outlier residuals (>±4,000 "kg" ) correspond to extreme yields (Table 9: minimum 1,220 kg, maximum 20,790 kg). For example, the test sample with the largest negative residual (-6,700 kg) had actual yield 20,790 kg (the maximum), which the model conservatively predicted at ~14,000 kg due to sparse training examples above 15,000 kg.
The validated Random Forest model (200 trees, max_depth=10, sqrt feature selection) achieving R^2=0.765 on the test set established the prediction performance baseline for the Python scikit-learn implementation. To enable offline yield prediction on Android devices (FR1), the model required conversion from Python to Java code via m2cgen. The following section presents the model export process and numerical parity validation to ensure the Java implementation preserved prediction accuracy.
 
Fig. 21. Residual plot for training (blue) and test (orange) sets. Vertical lines show error magnitudes relative to zero. Random scatter indicates no systematic bias.
Model export and parity validation
Following validation of the Random Forest model's predictive performance on the held-out test set, the model was exported from Python scikit-learn to Java code using m2cgen (Model to Code Generator, version 0.10.0) to enable offline prediction on Android devices without requiring internet connectivity (FR1) or server infrastructure.
The m2cgen library transpiled the trained Random Forest Regressor (200 trees, 27 input features, max_depth=10) into a standalone Java class containing a score(double[] features) method that implements the complete decision logic of all 200 trees without external dependencies. The exported code consists of nested if-else statements representing the decision tree structure, with feature thresholds and leaf values hardcoded from the trained model, enabling deterministic predictions identical to the original Python implementation.
To ensure conversion fidelity, numerical parity validation compared predictions between the original Python scikit-learn model and the exported Java implementation across all test set samples (n=17). The parity testing methodology, detailed in Appendix 8, involved extracting the 27 feature values for each test sample, executing both Python and Java predictions, and computing absolute differences and relative errors. A tolerance threshold of 0.01% was established as the acceptance criterion, consistent with industry standards for model deployment validation. 
Table 15 presents the parity validation results summarizing the comparison across all 17 test samples. For this test set, numerical parity was achieved, with observed absolute differences of 0.00 kg and relative errors of 0.0000% for every prediction (to the recorded precision). These results indicate that, for the evaluated samples, the Java implementation replicated the Python model’s outputs exactly, with no detectable rounding errors or implementation discrepancies within the chosen precision. The zero-difference outcome is well within the 0.01% tolerance threshold, supporting the conclusion that m2cgen’s code generation preserved the trained tree structure, feature thresholds, and leaf values for this model configuration.
This validation addressed the computational constraint, where m2cgen code generation file size limits necessitated restricting the model to ≤200 trees and max_depth ≤10. The successful parity validation confirmed that these constraints did not compromise prediction accuracy during conversion, and that the selected configuration (200 trees, depth 10) remained within m2cgen's operational limits while preserving the test set performance metrics documented in Table 14.
The validated Java model established the foundation for integration into the Android application architecture, where it operates completely offline without external libraries or network connectivity. The model receives farmer-provided feature values and generates yield predictions directly on the mobile device, eliminating the need for server infrastructure and enabling real-time decision support in areas with limited internet access.
Table 15. Numerical parity validation comparing Python scikit-learn and Java m2cgen predictions on test set (n=17 farms).
Statistic	Absolute Difference (kg)	Relative Error (%)
Mean	0.00	0.0000
Standard Deviation	0.00	0.0000
Maximum	0.00	0.0000
Minimum	0.00	0.0000
Samples passing tolerance (<0.01%)	17/17 (100%)	

Mobile Application Development
Following the derivation of functional and non-functional requirements from empirical farmer observations (Table 10-Table 11) and the validation of the Random Forest prediction model with numerical parity between the Python and Java implementations (Table 15), the construction phase translated these specifications into a working Android mobile application. The GabayPalay application was developed using Android Studio with Kotlin as the primary programming language, integrating the m2cgen-generated Java model directly into the application package to enable complete offline operation without internet dependency (FR1, NFR1). Development followed the Rapid Application Development construction phase methodology, with iterative functional testing culminating in deployment for user acceptance evaluation.
This section presents the system architecture and model integration, data flow and application workflow, functional requirements implementation with user interface evidence, non-functional requirements validation, and deployment procedures.
System architecture and model integration
The GabayPalay mobile application was implemented using a three-layer modular architecture (in Fig. 22) that separated user interface concerns from business logic and data management. This architectural approach enabled independent development and testing of each layer while supporting the offline operation requirement (NFR1) and facilitating validation of model accuracy independently from user interface usability.
The Data and Model Layer (Fig. 22, bottom section) contained the m2cgen-generated Model.java class implementing the Random Forest prediction algorithm (200 trees, max_depth=10, validated in Table 15) with a standalone score() method that accepts the 27-element feature vector and returns predicted yield in kilograms. The Java model file accounted for approximately 71% of the codebase by language composition, with application logic comprising 28.9% in Kotlin. The Android manifest declared no network permissions, ensuring complete offline operation as specified in FR1. Local data persistence was implemented using Android Room Persistence Library, a modern abstraction layer over SQLite that provided compile-time verification of SQL queries and simplified database operations.
 
Fig. 22. Three-layer modular architecture of the GabayPalay mobile application showing separation between User Interface Layer, Business Logic Layer, and Data and Model Layer with specific implementation classes, adapted from Gillis (2024).
The AppDatabase class extended RoomDatabase and defined two Data Access Object (DAO) interfaces: PredictionHistoryDao for managing prediction summary records in the prediction_history table and PredictionInputDao for managing complete farm input records in the prediction_inputs table. The HistoryManager singleton class wrapped these DAO operations, providing simplified methods (savePrediction(), getAllHistory(), setFavorite(), deletePrediction()) that the UI layer activities could invoke. Entity classes (PredictionHistoryEntity, PredictionInputEntity) defined the database table schemas with Room annotations, while corresponding domain model classes (PredictionHistory, PredictionInputs, PredictionResult, FertilizerApplication) represented the data structures used by business logic and UI layers. Type converters handled serialization of complex types (Date objects, List<String>) for database storage. This implementation enabled historical tracking (FR6) while maintaining all data on-device to address the privacy requirement (NFR4) and the connectivity constraints documented during requirements planning.
The Business Logic Layer (Fig. 22, middle section) was implemented primarily through the PredictionManager singleton object, the InputMapper utility class, and the FertilizerUtils utility class. The PredictionManager handled input validation, feature vector construction from user-provided data (X_1-X_27), model invocation via calculateYield(), and result interpretation through sensitivity analysis. The FertilizerUtils class provided automatic NPK nutrient calculation methods that computed total nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium quantities from fertilizer formulations and application amounts. Input validation verified that required fields contained valid positive numeric values to prevent erroneous entries while maintaining flexibility for the documented variability in farmer practices. The PredictionManager maintained application state across activity transitions using in-memory storage, enabling the staged input workflow (FR2) without requiring persistent storage until prediction completion. The InputMapper class provided utility methods for mapping data between Android Intent objects and the PredictionInputs data class during activity transitions. The automatic NPK calculation reduced the cognitive burden of manual nutrient computation for farmers unfamiliar with fertilizer chemistry, addressing the complexity identified during requirements planning.
The User Interface Layer (Fig. 22, top section) comprised nine primary Kotlin Activity classes implemented with Material Design 3 components and XML layouts: (1) MainActivity providing the application entry point and primary navigation, (2) PredictPalayActivity managing the optional onboarding flow for first-time users with a "Don't show again" preference, (3) PrePlantingActivity collecting land area, rice variety, seed amount, planting method, and land preparation inputs, (4) NutrientManagementActivity handling multi-application fertilizer tracking with automatic unit conversion between kilograms and sacks, (5) PestManagementActivity capturing pest identification and pesticide application data, (6) WeatherManagementActivity collecting the binary weather challenge indicator, (7) PreviewActivity displaying the comprehensive input review modal before prediction execution, (8) OutputActivity presenting prediction results with yield estimates, unit conversions, feature importance visualizations, insights, and recommendations, and (9) HistoryActivity managing the display and filtering of saved prediction records with favorites support. 
These activities organized the input workflow into dedicated screens corresponding to rice production stages identified during Phase 1 interviews. The UI maintained compatibility with Android 8.0 (API level 26) and above to accommodate the range of smartphone devices documented during Phase 1 farmer surveys, with target specifications set to ensure broad accessibility across device types available in the study area. The final APK size of 12.4 MB remained 75% below the 50 MB target specified in NFR1, enabling distribution via Bluetooth and social media messaging platforms to accommodate the connectivity constraints documented in Phase 1.
The implemented architecture supported the data flow shown in Fig. 22, where farmers provide farm inputs through the mobile interface (UI Layer activities), the PredictionManager validates and processes inputs locally (Business Logic Layer), the Model.java class generates predictions (Data and Model Layer), and the HistoryManager stores results via Room DAOs in the local SQLite database for historical review. No external data transmission occurs at any stage, satisfying both the offline operation requirement (FR1) and the data privacy requirement (NFR4) while eliminating dependency on internet connectivity documented as unreliable during Phase 1 investigations.
Data and application workflow
The implemented system processes farmer inputs through modular workflows organized by rice production activities, as illustrated in the data flow diagrams and control 
flow diagrams. All data processing occurs locally on the mobile device without external transmission, satisfying the offline operation requirement (FR1) and privacy protection requirement (NFR4) while addressing the connectivity constraints documented during Phase 1.
System context. The system context diagram (in Fig. 23) illustrates the application's boundary and its interaction with the external environment. The Farmer provides farm input data (land characteristics, rice variety, fertilizer applications, pest management practices, weather conditions) to the GabayPalay system, which processes this information entirely on-device and returns yield predictions, insights, and agronomic recommendations. No external systems, databases, or network services are involved in the data flow, reflecting the offline-first architecture that eliminates dependencies on internet connectivity or cloud infrastructure. This closed-loop design ensures that all sensitive farm data remains under the farmer's control on their personal device.
Internal system workflow. The internal workflow in Fig. 24 organized data collection into four input modules corresponding to the farming activities identified during Phase 1 interviews: pre-planting preparation (Process 1.0), fertilizer management (Process 2.0), pest management (Process 3.0), and environmental challenges (Process 4.0). Each module captured specific input variables from the feature set before aggregating them for yield prediction (Process 5.0). The palay yield prediction module executed the embedded Random Forest model via the PredictionManager.calculateYield() method, which invoked the Java model's score() function with the 27-element feature vector, and generated results that were saved to Local Storage along with the corresponding farm inputs through the HistoryManager.savePrediction() method. 
 
Fig. 23. Data flow diagram (DFD Level 0) showing the GabayPalay system context with the Farmer as the sole external entity interacting with the application through farm input data and receiving yield predictions and recommendations.
The yield prediction history module (Process 6.0) retrieved stored records from the SQLite database via HistoryManager.getAllHistory(), enabling farmers to review past inputs and compare scenarios across seasons. This architecture supported the experience-based, seasonal decision-making pattern observed among all interviewed farmers.
The fertilizer management module in Fig. 25 implemented the three-stage fertilization pattern universal among interviewed farmers (Table 7, Theme I9: 100% reported 2–3 stage fertilization). Farmers first specified the number of application splits (Sub-process 2.1), typically 2 or 3 applications corresponding to basal, mid-season, and late-season timings documented in Phase 1. 
 
Fig. 24. Data flow diagram (DFD Level 1) showing the six major functional modules of the GabayPalay application and their interactions with the Farmer and Local Storage.
 
Fig. 25. Detailed data flow diagram (DFD Level 2) for the Fertilizer Management module, showing automatic NPK nutrient calculation based on fertilizer formulation selection.
For each split, farmers selected the fertilizer formulation and measurement unit (Sub-process 2.2), choosing from five standardized products identified during requirements planning: Complete 14-14-14, Urea 46-0-0, Ammosul 21-0-0, Muriate of Potash 0-0-60, and Complete 16-20-0. The system automatically calculated total nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K) quantities per application (Sub-process 2.3) through the FertilizerUtils class methods based on the NPK ratio of the selected fertilizer and the entered amount, storing these computed nutrient values as three separate features (total N, total P, total K per application split) that contributed to the 27-element feature vector. This automatic calculation reduced the cognitive burden of manual nutrient computation for farmers unfamiliar with fertilizer chemistry.
Application control flow. User navigation through the application followed the control flow illustrated in Fig. 27-Fig. 32. The main navigation structure in Fig. 26 provided two primary pathways from the home screen: initiating a new yield prediction or reviewing historical predictions, corresponding to the two core use cases identified during requirements planning (FR1 and FR6). Users selected their intended action through prominent buttons implemented in MainActivity, with an additional option to exit the application.
Prediction workflow. The prediction workflow guided users through sequential input stages organized by the rice production activities documented in Phase 1: pre-planting preparation, nutrient management, pest management, and weather conditions. At each stage, input validation prevented progression with incomplete data while allowing backward navigation for corrections via Android's back button handling. The PredictionManager singleton maintained application state across activity transitions using in-memory storage, with each activity writing its validated inputs to the manager via dedicated setter methods before proceeding to the next stage.
 
Fig. 26. Main navigation control flow showing entry points for the prediction workflow (Fig. 27-Fig. 31) and history workflow (Fig. 32).
 
Fig. 27. Control flow for the pre-planting input stage showing onboarding, data entry, validation, and navigation to the nutrient management stage (Connector 1→A).
The workflow began with the pre-planting stage (in Fig. 27), implemented through PrePlantingActivity, which collected fundamental farm characteristics: land area in hectares, rice variety selection, seed amount in kilograms, planting method, and land preparation methods. First-time users were presented with an optional onboarding guide that introduced the staged input workflow, addressing the digital literacy constraints where 100% of interviewed farmers reported no prior agricultural application. The onboarding screen included a "Don't show again" preference stored via SharedPreferences that allowed experienced users to bypass the introduction on subsequent launches. Input validation verified that required fields contained valid positive numeric values, displaying contextual error messages through Material Design Toast notifications when fields were incomplete or contained non-numeric input, preventing form submission until all validation criteria were satisfied.
Following pre-planting validation, the workflow proceeded to the nutrient management stage (in Fig. 28), implemented through NutrientManagementActivity. This stage captured the multi-application fertilization pattern observed during Phase 1 investigations, beginning with selection of the number of fertilizer application splits (2 or 3). For each application, farmers selected fertilizer formulation via dropdown and entered quantities with unit selection (kilograms or 50-kilogram sacks) to accommodate the measurement variability documented during requirements planning. 
 
Fig. 28. Control flow for the nutrient management stage showing fertilizer split selection, iterative application entry with automatic NPK calculation, and navigation to the pest management stage (Connector A→B).
 
Fig. 29. Control flow for the pest management stage showing pest selection, pesticide quantity entry, validation, and navigation to the weather conditions stage (Connector B→C).
The FertilizerUtils class automatically calculated total NPK values (three N/P/K triplets for up to three application stages) based on the selected fertilizer's NPK ratio and entered quantity, displaying the computed nutrient amounts to provide transparency while reducing the cognitive burden of manual nutrient computation. The fertilizer management stage implemented a loop control that enforced the maximum number of application splits selected by the farmer, preventing accidental over-entry of fertilization data.
The pest management stage (in Fig. 29), implemented through PestManagementActivity, provided binary presence indicators for the five key pest and disease categories identified through analysis. The checkbox-based interface enabled farmers to indicate which pests were observed or anticipated during the cropping season, with corresponding input fields for protecting product quantities when pests were selected. 
 
Fig. 30. Control flow for the weather conditions stage showing binary weather challenge input and navigation to prediction execution (Connector C→P).
The weather conditions stage (in Fig. 30), implemented through WeatherActivity, captured the binary weather challenge indicator through a straightforward checkbox, consistent with the constraint analysis that excluded continuous weather variables due to limited local measurement infrastructure while retaining the farmer-reported binary indicator for flooding, drought, or typhoon impacts that affected 80% of survey respondents (Table 9).
Following completion of all input stages, the application proceeded to prediction execution (in Fig. 31). In OutputActivity, the validated inputs stored in PredictionManager were used to construct the 27-element feature vector, and PredictionManager invoked the embedded Java model’s score() method to generate the yield prediction and displayed results with multiple presentation layers: primary prediction prominently shown with practical unit conversions, confidence indicator derived from test set performance, prediction range visualization (±15% of point estimate), feature importance bar chart generated through dynamic sensitivity analysis, contextual insights using Material Design Chip components, and agronomic recommendations based on input patterns. Users then choose whether to navigate to the history view for scenario comparison (Connector P→2) or return to the main page (Connector P→M).
History management workflow. The history management workflow (in Fig. 32) retrieved all stored prediction records from the local SQLite database via HistoryManager.getAllHistory() and presented them in reverse chronological order through a RecyclerView adapter in HistoryActivity. When no historical data existed (typically for first-time users), the application displayed a clear message indicating that no history had been saved, with navigation options to return to the main page or initiate a new prediction. When historical data were available, users could apply filtering options to view all predictions, recent predictions, or favorites only. 
 
Fig. 31. Control flow for model execution and results display showing feature vector construction, prediction invocation, and navigation options (Connector P→M/2).
 
Fig. 32. Control flow for the prediction history management workflow showing database retrieval, filtering options, and record actions (Connector 2→M).
For each displayed record, users could tap to view full prediction details through PreviewActivity in history mode, compare scenarios across seasons supporting the longitudinal decision-making pattern identified in Phase 1, mark predictions as favorites for quick reference via the HistoryManager.setFavorite() method, or delete outdated records through the HistoryManager.deletePrediction() method invoked from long-press context menus. The history interface provided backward navigation through the Android back button that allowed users to return to the main page or continue reviewing stored predictions.
The implemented data flow and control flow architecture ensured that farmer inputs progressed systematically through validation, processing, and storage stages without requiring internet connectivity or external services. This design satisfied the functional requirements for offline prediction (FR1), stage-based input management (FR2), and historical record management (FR6), while supporting the usability requirements (NFR2) through clear navigation pathways, Material Design components, and error prevention mechanisms.
Functional requirements implementation and user interface
All six functional requirements derived from Phase 1 empirical analysis were implemented and verified through pre-deployment testing. This section presents the implementation evidence for each requirement with supporting user interface screenshots.
Requirement FR1: Offline Yield Prediction Capability. The application implemented complete offline prediction functionality by embedding the m2cgen-generated Java Random Forest model directly in the application package, with no network permissions declared in the Android manifest file. As shown in Fig. 33b, the home screen provided immediate access to the "Predict Palay Yield" function without requiring login, internet connectivity, or external service dependencies. 
 
