(b)
Fig. 34. Pre-planting input interface implementing Requirement FR3 (Rice Variety Classification and Seed Rate Management). (a) Data entry form displaying fields for land area, rice variety dropdown, seed amount, planting method dropdown, and land preparation checkboxes; (b) Input validation error feedback highlighting incomplete required field with contextual error message. 
kilograms with automatic sack conversion, planting method via dropdown, and land preparation method checkboxes. Input validation verified that required fields contained valid positive numeric values, displaying contextual error messages (Fig. 34b) through Material Design Toast notifications when fields were incomplete or contained non-numeric input, preventing form submission until all validation criteria were satisfied (NFR5: error resilience).
Requirement FR2: Stage-Based Agricultural Input Management. The nutrient management interface (Fig. 35) implemented in NutrientManagementActivity captured the three-stage fertilization pattern observed in 100% of farmer interviews (Table 6, Theme I9). The workflow began with selection of the number of fertilizer application splits (Fig. 35a), with options for 2 or 3 applications corresponding to the basal, mid-season, and late-season timings documented in Phase 1 (Table 9). For each selected split, farmers provided fertilizer type via dropdown (Fig. 35b) choosing from five standardized formulations (Complete 14-14-14, Urea 46-0-0, Ammosul 21-0-0, Muriate of Potash 0-0-60, Complete 16-20-0) and quantity with unit selection (Fig. 35d-e) supporting both kilograms and 50-kilogram sacks to accommodate the measurement variability documented during requirements planning. The FertilizerUtils class automatically calculated total NPK values (three N/P/K triplets for up to three application stages) based on the selected fertilizer's NPK ratio and entered quantity, displaying the computed nutrient amounts to provide transparency while reducing the cognitive burden of manual nutrient computation. The completed nutrient management form displayed all application details with computed NPK totals before proceeding to the next stage.
Requirement FR4: Pest, Disease, and Water Management Recording. The pest management interface (Fig. 36) implemented in PestManagementActivity provided binary presence indicators for the five key pest and disease categories identified through thematic analysis: stem borer, rats, golden apple snail/kuhol, cutworms, and rice blast. The checkbox-based interface (Fig. 36a-b) enabled farmers to indicate which pests were observed or anticipated during the cropping season, with corresponding input fields for protection product quantities when pests were selected. This design reflected the IPM orientation documented in Phase 1, where 10 out of 11 interviewed farmers (Table 6, Theme I4) reported limited routine insecticide use with preventive timing emphasis rather than calendar-based spraying schedules. 
 
