Fig. 36. Pest management interface implementing Requirement FR4 (Pest, Disease, and Water Management Recording). (a) Blank pest management form displaying checkbox groups for five common pests and diseases aligned with Phase 1 thematic findings; (b) Completed form showing selected pest indicators and corresponding protection product quantities.
The weather conditions screen (Fig. 37) implemented in WeatherActivity captured the binary weather challenge indicator through a straightforward checkbox, consistent with the constraint analysis (Table 8) that excluded continuous weather variables (rainfall, temperature, floods, typhoon, drought, etc.) due to limited local measurement infrastructure while retaining the farmer-reported binary indicator for flooding, drought, or typhoon impacts that affected 43 of 54 survey respondents (79.6%, Table 9).
 
Fig. 37. Weather conditions input screen implementing the binary weather challenge indicator identified during requirements planning.
Following completion of all input stages, the application presented a comprehensive review modal (Fig. 38a) implemented through PreviewActivity that displayed all entered data organized by category (pre-planting, nutrient management, pest management, weather conditions). This review interface provided a final verification opportunity before prediction execution, enabling users to identify and correct errors across all input categories in a single consolidated view. Upon confirmation, the PredictionManager.generatePrediction() method constructed the 27-element feature vector, invoked the embedded Java model's score() method, and returned a PredictionResult object containing the predicted yield, confidence score, insights, and recommendations.
 
(a)	 
(c)	 
(d)
 
(b)		
Fig. 38. Input review and prediction interfaces for Requirement FR5 (Transparent Results). (a) Review modal summarizing categorized farm inputs before prediction; (b) Simple results display with predicted yield, unit conversions, and confidence; (c) Detailed results view with prediction range, insights, and recommendations; (d) Feature importance visualization showing relative influence of 27 inputs, generated via dynamic sensitivity analysis.
Requirement FR5: Transparent Prediction Result Presentation. The results interface (Fig. 38b-c) implemented in OutputActivity provided multi-level transparency to address trust concerns identified during requirements planning. The simple results view (Fig. 38b) displayed the primary prediction prominently with practical unit conversions: yield in kilograms (model output), and sacks (÷50 kg, on-farm storage unit), enabling farmers to conceptualize the prediction in familiar terms. The confidence indicator, derived from the test set R² of 0.765 (Table 15), provided context for prediction reliability by reminding users of the model’s overall performance on unseen data. The detailed results view (Fig. 38c) expanded the presentation with a prediction range visualization (±15% of point estimate with headroom adjustment) implemented through custom view drawing that displayed the prediction as a vertical bar chart with upper and lower bounds, supporting the scenario analysis use case where farmers mentally bracket expected outcomes.
The feature importance visualization (Fig. 38d) represented a key transparency mechanism that translated the Random Forest model's internal importance scores into an accessible horizontal bar chart. Rather than relying solely on the static feature importances from the Python training phase, the application implemented dynamic sensitivity analysis through the PredictionManager.computeFeatureImportance() method, which perturbed each input feature by ±10% and measured the resulting change in predicted yield, ranking features by their marginal impact on the specific prediction. This approach provided personalized explanations showing which agronomic factors most strongly influenced the particular yield estimate. 
Requirement FR6: Historical Prediction Record Management. The history management interface (Fig. 39) implemented in HistoryActivity provided persistent local storage of prediction sessions through the HistoryManager class and Room database. The history list view (Fig. 39a-b) displayed saved predic stions in reverse chronological order with key summary information: timestamp, predicted yield, and favorite status indicator. The favorites feature (Fig. 39c) enabled farmers to bookmark particularly informative predictions for quick reference via the HistoryManager.setFavorite() method, supporting the scenario comparison use case identified during requirements planning where farmers mentally compared input variations. Tapping any history record opened the full prediction details through PreviewActivity in history mode, which displayed both the original inputs and prediction results without recalculation, enabling farmers to review past estimates and compare them with actual outcomes at harvest time.
 
(a)	 
(b)	 
(c)
Fig. 39. Prediction history interface for Requirement FR6: (a) History list showing the recent saved entry with timestamp, yield, and favorite toggle; (b) List displaying all predictions (reverse chronological); (c) Favorites view filtering bookmarked scenarios.
The implemented user interface successfully operationalized all functional requirements through a combination of Material Design 3 components (MaterialAlertDialogBuilder, Chips, dropdowns, checkboxes), custom validation logic, automatic calculation features, and persistent local storage. The staged workflow organization aligned with the rice production activities familiar to farmers from Phase 1 interviews, while the transparency mechanisms (unit conversions, prediction ranges, feature importance, contextual insights) addressed the trust and interpretability concerns documented during requirements planning.
The implementation approach prioritized clear separation of concerns through the three-layer architecture, with the PredictionManager singleton class serving as the primary Business Logic component that coordinated data flow between the User Interface activities and the embedded Data/Model layer. Key implementation details demonstrating novel approaches for feature vector construction, dynamic sensitivity analysis, automatic NPK calculation via FertilizerUtils, and state management across the sequential workflow are presented in Appendix 9.
Non-functional requirements validation
The implemented application was designed to address the non-functional requirements specified during requirements planning (Table 11). This subsection summarizes how the current version of GabayPalay aligns with these requirements based on manifest inspection, code review, and pre-deployment manual testing. Table 16 summarizes the observed behavior of the prototype relative to the target specifications.
NFR1: Device Compatibility and Resource Optimization. The application supports Android 8.0 (API level 26) and above, covering the range of devices reported in Phase 1 surveys. The release APK size of 12.4 MB is well below the 50 MB target specified during requirements planning, facilitating offline distribution via Bluetooth and social media messaging platforms (e.g., Facebook Messenger). During manual testing on the available devices, no memory-related issues were observed when performing typical tasks such as entering inputs, generating predictions, and browsing history, suggesting that the application operates within the intended resource constraints for low-spec devices.
Table 16. Non-functional requirements validation results showing achieved specifications against target values for the GabayPalay mobile application.
ID	Requirement	Achieved / Status
NFR1	Device Compatibility and Resource Use	Supports Android 8.0 (API 26) and above; release APK size is 12.4 MB (well below the 50 MB target). No memory-related issues were observed during manual testing on typical farmer devices.
NFR2	Usability and Accessibility	Implements a staged, activity-based workflow with Material Design 3 components and clear navigation. Informal testing indicated that farmers could follow the workflow, but formal SUS scoring and potential Bisaya localization are deferred to the user acceptance and usability evaluation phase.
NFR3	Prediction Performance	Prediction responses appeared almost instantaneous and subjectively within the 3-second target during manual tests. The embedded m2cgen Java model produced numerically equivalent outputs to the Python baseline on the validation set (see Table 15). No formal performance profiling was conducted.
NFR4	Data Security and Privacy	No network permissions are declared; all data are stored locally using Room/SQLite in the app’s private directory, and no external SDKs or analytics are integrated. SQLite-level encryption was not implemented; instead, the prototype relies on Android’s application sandbox for data isolation.
NFR5	System Reliability and Error Handling	Input validation and contextual error messages were verified through manual negative testing (invalid/missing inputs). Basic try–catch handling is in place around critical operations, and no crashes were observed in the pre-deployment test scenarios, although exhaustive stress testing was not performed.

NFR2: Usability and Accessibility. The user interface employs a staged, activity-based workflow aligned with farming activities (pre-planting, fertilization, pest management, weather), using Material Design 3 components and clear navigation from the main screen to prediction and history functions. Informal testing by the researcher and initial use by farmers indicated that the workflow and labels were understandable, particularly when combined with the optional onboarding guide for first-time users. However, the current implementation uses English for all text and labels, while detailed SUS-based usability evaluation with farmers is reported in the subsequent chapter. Comprehensive usability assessment, including SUS scoring and exploration of Bisaya or mixed-language labels, is deferred to the user acceptance testing and usability evaluation presented in the next chapter.
NFR3: Prediction Performance and Responsiveness. No formal performance profiling (e.g., instrumented timing or benchmark scripts) was conducted. Nevertheless, during manual testing on the available devices, yield predictions were generated almost instantaneously and subjectively within the 3-second response time target, even when navigating through the full input workflow. The embedded m2cgen-generated Java model produced numerically equivalent outputs to the Python baseline on the 17 test samples used for parity checking (Table 15), indicating that the conversion process preserved prediction behavior for the evaluated cases. These observations suggest that the prototype’s prediction performance is adequate for interactive use in the intended deployment context, although more rigorous profiling could further quantify performance under a broader range of hardware configurations.
NFR4: Data Security and Privacy. Manifest inspection and code review confirmed that the application declares no network permissions and integrates no external analytics, advertising, or crash-reporting SDKs. All user data (farm inputs and prediction results) are stored locally via the Room persistence library in the application’s private directory, which is not accessible to other applications under normal conditions. This design enforces local-only storage and zero external transmission, addressing privacy and trust concerns raised during interviews and informed consent discussions. Full SQLite encryption was not implemented in the current prototype; instead, data protection relies on Android’s default application sandbox model. As such, the implementation meets the core requirement of local-only, offline data handling, while stronger encryption could be considered in future versions to further enhance data security.
NFR5: System Reliability and Error Handling. Input validation is applied at each stage of the workflow to prevent incomplete or invalid submissions. Manual negative testing (e.g., leaving required fields blank, entering non-numeric values where numbers are expected) confirmed that the application displays contextual error messages and prevents progression until issues are corrected. The PredictionManager maintains application state across activities, allowing users to navigate backward without losing entered data. Basic try–catch constructs are wrapped around critical operations such as database access and model invocation, and no crashes were observed during the pre-deployment test scenarios conducted by the researcher. However, exhaustive automated stress testing and long-term field reliability monitoring were beyond the scope of this study and are identified as areas for future work.
The observed behavior of the implemented application indicates that the targeted non-functional requirements are reasonably addressed within the limits of the current prototype, the tested devices, and the scope of pre-deployment evaluation. Offline operation and on-device data handling directly respond to connectivity and privacy constraints identified in Phase 1, while usability, performance, and reliability have been validated at an initial level and are further examined through structured user acceptance and usability evaluation in the subsequent chapter.
Application deployment and distribution
The completed application was packaged as an Android APK file for distribution to study participants. The deployment process prioritized accessibility in light of the connectivity constraints and device diversity documented during Phase 1.
The final release APK was generated through Android Studio’s build system with a release signing configuration, producing a 12.4 MB package compatible with devices running Android 8.0 (API level 26) and above. This compatibility threshold encompassed the range of smartphone models reported by farmers in the study area during the Phase 1 surveys. The application was not published to the Google Play Store in order to avoid the requirement for active Google accounts and potential additional configuration overhead, which could have introduced barriers to adoption given the digital literacy constraints observed in Phase 1 (Table 6, Theme I12: 100% reported no prior agricultural app usage).
Distribution employed three complementary channels to accommodate farmer preferences and existing technology use patterns: (1) direct installation via laptop during face-to-face meetings with farmers, which allowed the researcher to assist with installation and demonstrate initial usage; (2) Bluetooth file transfer for farmers who preferred to install the application on their own devices without relying on internet connectivity; and (3) sharing via social media messaging platforms (e.g., Facebook Messenger) for farmers who were already comfortable downloading and opening files received through these channels. These distribution methods aligned with the communication patterns observed during Phase 1, where farmers frequently shared agricultural information and photos through messaging groups.
Installation instructions were provided verbally and visually during farmer meetings that illustrated the steps for enabling installation from unknown sources in Android settings, locating the downloaded APK file, and granting the necessary permissions during installation. The instructions emphasized that the application did not require an internet connection after installation and that all data would remain stored locally on the farmer’s device.
This deployment approach successfully delivered the application to the intended study participants while respecting the technological constraints and preferences documented during requirements planning. It also established the foundation for the subsequent user acceptance testing and usability evaluation, during which farmers’ actual experiences with the installed application (including language clarity, ease of use, and perceived usefulness) could be systematically assessed.
User Acceptance Testing and Usability Evaluation
Following implementation and internal validation of the GabayPalay application, user acceptance testing was conducted with rice farmers from Hagonoy, Davao del Sur to evaluate usability, perceived usefulness, and adoption potential. This section presents the results of RAD Phase 4 (Cutover and Validation), including participant characteristics, quantitative usability assessment using the System Usability Scale (SUS), technology acceptance evaluation using the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM), qualitative user feedback, and task completion analysis that are briefly described in Appendix 10. The user evaluation provides empirical evidence for Requirement NFR2.
Participant demographics and characteristics
User acceptance testing involved 36 rice farmers from Hagonoy, Davao del Sur. Participants were identified with the help of associations and cooperatives, following the sampling procedures described in the methodology. Participants were drawn from the same locality as the Phase 1 interview (n = 11) and survey (n = 54) respondents, ensuring consistency in farming practices, environmental conditions, and technology access patterns that informed the requirements specification. Table 17 summarizes the demographic characteristics of the UAT participants.
The sample was predominantly male (83.3%), reflecting typical gender roles in farm management in Philippine rice systems. Ages ranged from early twenties to late fifties, with balanced representation across age cohorts. Educational attainment was mainly elementary and high school level (80.5% combined), similar to the Phase 1 survey profile, and consistent with the digital literacy constraints that motivated simplified interaction patterns under NFR2.
Daily smartphone usage was concentrated in the 1-3 hour range (38.9%), with over one-quarter of participants using smartphones less than 1 hour per day. This distribution indicates moderate but not intensive digital engagement and underscores the need for interfaces that remain usable for users with limited technology exposure. Prior agricultural app use was rare; 86.1% reported never having used any agricultural mobile application, while a small subset had experience with tools such as Rice Doctor, Rice Crop Manager, PlantNet, RiceAdvice, and postharvest quality tools. Farming experience ranged from 2 to 35 years (median 18 years), and farm sizes were characteristic of smallholder systems, with most participants managing 1–3 hectares. Overall, the UAT sample reflects the diversity and constraints of the intended user population.
