System Usability Scale assessment
The System Usability Scale (SUS) was used to quantify perceived usability. The instrument consists of ten items rated on a five-point Likert scale, converted to a composite score from 0 to 100 following Brooke's (1996) standard procedure. Summary statistics for the SUS scores of the 36 farmer participants are presented in Table 18. Item-level SUS responses, which provide more detailed insight into specific usability aspects such as ease of use, complexity, and need for support, are shown in Table 19.
The mean SUS score of 60.3 (SD = 19.5) is below the commonly cited benchmark of approximately 68 for clearly acceptable usability and below the target specified in NFR2. Using the interpretive ranges suggested by Bangor et al. (2009), this value corresponds to marginal to acceptable usability. The wide range (27.5 to 100.0) and high standard deviation indicate substantial variability in user experience: 41.7% of participants rated the system at or above 70, and 16.7% rated it at or above 80, while others assigned much lower scores. In the present sample, younger farmers, those with higher educational attainment, and those with more intensive smartphone use tended to assign higher SUS scores and to complete the workflow with fewer difficulties. This pattern is consistent with reports that usability and technology adoption in agriculture are strongly associated with education level and digital literacy (Angchay et al., 2024; Gabrillo and Torres, 2022). 
In contrast, elementary-educated farmers with less than one hour of daily smartphone usage often provided low SUS ratings and required more guidance. These findings align with the digital literacy and adoption constraints identified in the requirements phase and confirm that the interface is usable for a portion of the target population but challenging for users at the lower end of the digital literacy spectrum.
Table 18. Summary statistics for System Usability Scale scores (n = 36).
Overall SUS Score	Value	Interpretation
Mean SUS Score	60.3	Below acceptable threshold (Brooke, 1996; Bangor et al., 2009)
Standard Deviation	19.5	High variability across users
Minimum Score	27.5	Lowest individual rating
Maximum Score	100.0	Highest individual rating (perfect score)
Median Score	58.8	Central tendency indicator
Scores ≥70 (Acceptable)	15 (41.7%)	Proportion meeting acceptability threshold
Scores ≥80 (Excellent)	6 (16.7%)	Proportion rating as excellent

Item-level (shown in Table 19) means indicate generally positive responses to statements about ease of use, integration, and confidence (SUS3, SUS5, SUS7, SUS9), but also reveal concerns about needing technical support and the learning effort required (SUS4, SUS10). The relatively low scores for perceived inconsistency and cumbersomeness (SUS6, SUS8) suggest that the interface is structurally coherent, but that complexity arises from content and task demands rather than from inconsistent layout.
The SUS results indicate that GabayPalay has achieved moderate but not yet optimal usability. The system satisfies NFR2 only partially: the staged workflow and Material Design components help many users complete tasks, but additional refinements are needed to make the interface consistently usable across the full range of farmers.
Technology Acceptance Model evaluation
User acceptance was further evaluated using the Technology Acceptance Model. Perceived Usefulness (PU) and Perceived Ease of Use (PEOU) were each measured through five items on a five-point Likert scale. Table 20 summarizes the TAM results.

Table 19. Item-level System Usability Scale (SUS) scores for GabayPalay (n = 36).
Individual SUS Items*	Mean Score	Interpretation
SUS1	3.53	Moderate positive intention
SUS2	2.81	Moderate complexity perception
SUS3	3.75	Moderate to high ease of use perception
SUS4	3.19	Moderate support dependency
SUS5	3.58	Good integration perception
SUS6	2.50	Low inconsistency perception
SUS7	3.58	Moderate learnability perception
SUS8	2.50	Low awkwardness perception
SUS9	3.78	Moderate to high confidence
SUS10	3.11	Moderate learning barrier
* Complete SUS item statements are included in Appendix 6.
PU scores were generally high, with most items receiving mean ratings close to or above 4.0. These patterns suggest that farmers recognized GabayPalay as a helpful decision-support tool, especially for estimating potential yield and planning fertilizer use. This observation is consistent with the documented need for more systematic input planning and yield prediction in smallholder rice farming and supports the design choices underlying the application’s core functions, such as offline yield prediction, stage-based input management, and the provision of clear prediction outputs and historical records.
PEOU scores were comparatively lower and more varied. The overall PEOU mean of 3.37 reflects a moderate level of ease of use. Item-level means suggest that most users were able to learn and navigate the system, but that several parts of the workflow required noticeable effort. These results align with the SUS findings and with qualitative feedback, where users frequently mentioned difficulties with fertilizer selection, switching between kilograms and sacks, interpreting the NPK display, and understanding some aspects of the prediction results. Farmers with greater smartphone experience and higher educational attainment tended to report fewer issues, while those with elementary education or limited daily smartphone use more often expressed uncertainty and required assistance.
Within the TAM framework, the combination of relatively high PU and only moderate PEOU indicates that GabayPalay offers a clear value proposition but that ease-of-use limitations may restrict wider and sustained adoption. Farmers appear willing to invest effort to use the application because they perceive concrete benefits in terms of planning and accuracy; however, the current usability level still poses challenges for users with lower digital literacy. This configuration is similar to patterns reported in other agricultural technology studies, where functional advantages can motivate initial trial, but improvements in ease of use, clarity, and cognitive load are important for encouraging continued independent use and peer recommendation.
